Date:  2 Feb 93 09:05:04 GMT
rick@ee.uwm.edu (Rick Miller) writes:

> There are two ways to shorten the signature:
> 	1.) decrease the bit-width of the hash-function used on the message
> 	2.) (I think...) use a smaller (less bits) key-pair.

2.) is just plain silly. We should use a variation of 1.) - for
instance, use only the leftmost (or any other) 64 bits of the MD5
digest of the message.

> Both methods not only reduce the confidence which one can have in the
> signature, but they also increase the risk of exposing your private key!

How?? You are encrypting a shorter message (a shorter output from the
hash function), so the probability that somebody will break it is even
smaller! It doesn't expose your private key in any way, it just makes
it relatively easier to forge a message. But you are warned about that
- - by the header that says "short signature"...

Regards,
Vesselin

